7. Security
	•	Protocols: Secure communication using SSL (illustrated with SSL badge)
	•	Access Management: Role-based access via PAM (Privileged Access Management)
	•	Monitoring: Centralized monitoring from the Kuwait Jump Machine

⸻

8. Notes
	•	All communication across regions is securely encrypted.
	•	Monitoring and bot deployment are centralized through Kuwait infrastructure.
	•	The load balancer ensures high availability and fault tolerance of BP application services.

To set up and configure Blue Prism Runtime Resources (also called Digital Workers or Runtime Machines), follow these essential steps:

⸻

1. Prepare the Environment
	•	Install Blue Prism: Install the Blue Prism software on each Runtime Resource machine.
	•	System Requirements: Ensure the machine meets the required hardware and software prerequisites (e.g., Windows OS, .NET Framework, etc.).
	•	Network Access: Ensure the machine can connect to the Blue Prism Application Server (or directly to the Database, if no app server is used).

⸻

2. Create Runtime Resource User Accounts
	•	Windows User: Create a dedicated Windows user account for each runtime resource.
	•	Blue Prism User: Create a corresponding Blue Prism user (if not using SSO) or assign the Windows account in Blue Prism’s user roles.

⸻

3. Configure the Runtime Resource Machine
	•	Login Agent (optional): Install and configure the Blue Prism Login Agent if robots need to log in automatically.
	•	Disable Sleep/Auto-lock: Ensure the system doesn’t auto-lock or go to sleep, which may interrupt automation.

⸻

4. Connect to the Environment
	•	Command Line Execution: Use the following command to run the Blue Prism client in resource mode:
•	Firewall & Ports: Ensure port 8181 (default) is open to allow communication between the Control Room and Runtime Resource.

⸻

5. Register the Runtime Resource
	•	Once started in resource mode, it should appear in Control Room > Resources in Blue Prism.
	•	If it doesn’t appear, check firewall, network, and correct command execution.

⸻

6. Test the Resource
	•	From Control Room, right-click on the runtime resource and choose “Start” with a sample process to verify it’s working.
